{"nodes":[{"content":"Test with the Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile","pos":[78,132]},{"content":"Simulate real-world interaction with a device and test the features of your app by using the tools included with Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[146,300]},{"content":"Test with the Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile","pos":[307,361]},{"content":"Updated for UWP apps on Windows 10.","pos":[366,401]},{"content":"For Windows 8.x articles, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>archive<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132)</ept>","pos":[402,494]},{"content":"Simulate real-world interaction with a device and test the features of your app by using the tools included with Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[499,653]},{"content":"The emulator is a desktop application that emulates a mobile device running Windows 10.","pos":[654,741]},{"content":"It provides a virtualized environment in which you can debug and test Windows apps without a physical device.","pos":[742,851]},{"content":"It also provides an isolated environment for your application prototypes.","pos":[852,925]},{"content":"The emulator is designed to provide comparable performance to an actual device.","pos":[927,1006]},{"content":"Before you publish your app to the Windows Store, however, we recommend that you test your app on a physical device.","pos":[1007,1123]},{"content":"You can test your universal app using a unique Windows 10 Mobile emulator image for various screen resolution and screen size configurations.","pos":[1125,1266]},{"content":"You can simulate real-world interaction with a device and test various features of your app by using the tools included in the Microsoft Emulator.","pos":[1267,1413]},{"content":"System requirements","pos":[1418,1437]},{"content":"Your computer must meet the following requirements:","pos":[1439,1490]},{"content":"BIOS","pos":[1492,1496]},{"content":"Hardware-assisted virtualization.","pos":[1502,1535]},{"content":"Second Level Address Translation (SLAT).","pos":[1540,1580]},{"content":"Hardware-based Data Execution Prevention (DEP).","pos":[1585,1632]},{"content":"RAM","pos":[1634,1637]},{"content":"4 GB or more.","pos":[1643,1656]},{"content":"Operating system","pos":[1658,1674]},{"content":"Windows 8 or higher (Windows 10 strongly recommended)","pos":[1680,1733]},{"content":"64-bit","pos":[1738,1744]},{"content":"Pro edition or higher","pos":[1749,1770]},{"pos":[1772,1937],"content":"To check the BIOS requirements, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to enable Hyper-V for the emulator for Windows Phone 8<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/jj863509.aspx)</ept>."},{"pos":[1939,2066],"content":"To check requirements for RAM and operating system, in Control Panel, click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>System and Security<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>System<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile requires Visual Studio 2015; it is not backward compatible with earlier versions of Visual Studio.","pos":[2068,2207]},{"content":"Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile cannot load apps that target the Windows Phone OS version earlier than Windows Phone OS 7.1.","pos":[2209,2342]},{"content":"Installing and uninstalling","pos":[2347,2374]},{"pos":[2380,2395],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Installing<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile ships as part of the Windows 10 SDK.","pos":[2401,2478]},{"content":"The Windows 10 SDK and emulator can be installed as part of the Visual Studio 2015 install.","pos":[2479,2570]},{"content":"See the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Visual Studio download page<ept id=\"p1\">](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=534785)</ept>.","pos":[2571,2659]},{"content":"You can also install the Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile using the Microsoft Emulator setup.","pos":[2665,2766]},{"content":"See the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows 10 Tools download page<ept id=\"p1\">](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkID=534189)</ept>.","pos":[2767,2858]},{"pos":[2864,2881],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Uninstalling<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"You can uninstall the Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile using Visual Studio setup/repair.","pos":[2887,2983]},{"content":"Or you can use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Programs and Features<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> under <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Control Panel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> to remove the emulator.","pos":[2984,3072]},{"content":"When you uninstall the Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile, the Hyper-V Virtual Ethernet Adapter that was created for the emulator to use is not automatically removed.","pos":[3078,3250]},{"content":"You can manually remove this virtual adapter from <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Network Connections<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> in <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Control Panel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[3251,3346]},{"content":"What’s new in Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile","pos":[3351,3405]},{"content":"In addition to providing support for Universal Windows Platform (UWP), the emulator has added the following functionality:","pos":[3407,3529]},{"content":"Mouse input mode support to differentiate between mouse and single touch input.","pos":[3535,3614]},{"content":"NFC Support.","pos":[3619,3631]},{"content":"The emulator allows you to simulate NFC and make it possible to test and develop NFC/Proximity-enabled universal apps.","pos":[3632,3750]},{"content":"Native hardware acceleration improves graphics performance in the emulator by using the local graphics card.","pos":[3755,3863]},{"content":"You must have a supported graphics card installed, and enable acceleration on the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Sensors<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab of the emulator's <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Additional Tools<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> settings user interface in order to use acceleration.","pos":[3864,4054]},{"content":"Features that you can test in the emulator","pos":[4059,4101]},{"content":"In addition to the new features mentioned in the previous section, you can test the following commonly used features in the Microsoft Emulator for Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[4103,4268]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Screen resolution, screen size, and memory<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[4274,4321]},{"content":"Reach a broad market for your app by testing it on various emulator images to simulate various screen resolutions, physical sizes, and memory constraints.","pos":[4322,4476]},{"content":"Available emulators with resolution, size, and memory","pos":[4484,4537]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Screen configuration<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[4564,4589]},{"content":"Change the emulator from portrait to landscape mode.","pos":[4590,4642]},{"content":"Change the zoom setting to fit the emulator to your desktop screen.","pos":[4643,4710]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Networking<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[4716,4731]},{"content":"Networking support is integrated with Windows Phone Emulator.","pos":[4732,4793]},{"content":"Networking is enabled by default.","pos":[4794,4827]},{"content":"You do not have to install network drivers for Windows Phone Emulator or configure networking options manually in most environments.","pos":[4828,4960]},{"content":"The emulator uses the network connection of the host computer.","pos":[4966,5028]},{"content":"It does not appear as a separate device on the network.","pos":[5029,5084]},{"content":"This eliminates some of the configuration issues that users encountered with the Windows Phone SDK 8.0 emulator.","pos":[5085,5197]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Language and region settings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[5203,5236]},{"content":"Prepare your app for an international market by changing the display language and region settings in Windows Phone Emulator.","pos":[5237,5361]},{"content":"On the running emulator, go to the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Settings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> app, then select the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>system<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> settings, then select <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>language<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> or <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>region<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>.","pos":[5367,5496]},{"content":"Change the settings that you want to test.","pos":[5497,5539]},{"content":"If you're prompted, click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>restart phone<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to apply the new settings and restart the emulator.","pos":[5540,5635]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Application lifecycle and tombstoning<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[5641,5683]},{"content":"Test the behavior or your app when it's deactivated or tombstoned by changing the value of the option <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Tombstone upon deactivation while debugging<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> on the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Debug<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> page of project properties.","pos":[5684,5878]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Local folder storage (previously known as isolated storage)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[5884,5948]},{"content":"Data in isolated storage persists while the emulator is running, but is lost once the emulator closes.","pos":[5949,6051]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Microphone<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[6057,6072]},{"content":"Requires and uses the microphone on the host computer.","pos":[6073,6127]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Phone keyboard<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[6133,6152]},{"content":"The emulator supports mapping of the hardware keyboard on your development computer to the keyboard on a Windows Phone.","pos":[6153,6272]},{"content":"The behavior of the keys is the same as on a Windows Phone device","pos":[6273,6338]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Lock screen<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[6344,6360]},{"content":"With the emulator open, press F12 on your computer keyboard twice.","pos":[6361,6427]},{"content":"The F12 key emulates the power button on the phone.","pos":[6428,6479]},{"content":"The first key press turns off the display.","pos":[6480,6522]},{"content":"The second key press turns the display on again with the lock screen engaged.","pos":[6523,6600]},{"content":"Unlock the screen by using the mouse to slide the lock screen upward.","pos":[6601,6670]},{"content":"Features that you can't test in the emulator","pos":[6675,6719]},{"content":"Test the following features only on a physical device.","pos":[6721,6775]},{"content":"Compass","pos":[6781,6788]},{"content":"Gyroscope","pos":[6793,6802]},{"content":"Vibration controller","pos":[6807,6827]},{"content":"Brightness.","pos":[6832,6843]},{"content":"The brightness level of the emulator is always High.","pos":[6844,6896]},{"content":"High-resolution video.","pos":[6901,6923]},{"content":"Videos with a resolution higher than VGA resolution (640 x 480) cannot be displayed reliably, especially on emulator images with only 512MB of memory.","pos":[6924,7074]},{"content":"Mouse input","pos":[7079,7090]},{"content":"Simulate mouse input using the physical mouse or trackpad on your Windows PC and the mouse input button on the emulator toolbar.","pos":[7092,7220]},{"content":"This feature is useful if your app provides the user with an ability to utilize a mouse paired to their Windows 10 device to provide input.","pos":[7221,7360]},{"content":"Tap the mouse input button on the emulator toolbar to enable mouse input.","pos":[7362,7435]},{"content":"Any click events within the emulator chrome will now be sent to the Windows 10 Mobile OS running inside the emulator VM as mouse events.","pos":[7436,7572]},{"content":"Emulator screen with mouse input enabled","pos":[7576,7616]},{"content":"The emulator screen with the mouse input enabled.","pos":[7659,7708]},{"content":"The mouse input button on the emulator toolbar","pos":[7712,7758]},{"content":"The mouse input button on the emulator toolbar.","pos":[7813,7860]},{"content":"Keyboard input","pos":[7865,7879]},{"content":"The emulator supports mapping of the hardware keyboard on your development computer to the keyboard on a Windows Phone.","pos":[7881,8000]},{"content":"The behavior of the keys is the same as on a Windows Phone device.","pos":[8001,8067]},{"content":"By default, the hardware keyboard is not enabled.","pos":[8070,8119]},{"content":"This implementation is equivalent to a sliding keyboard that must be deployed before you can use it.","pos":[8120,8220]},{"content":"Before you enable the hardware keyboard, the emulator accepts key input only from the control keys.","pos":[8221,8320]},{"content":"Special characters on the keyboard of a localized version of a Windows development computer are not supported by the emulator.","pos":[8322,8448]},{"content":"To enter special characters that are present on a localized keyboard, use the Software Input Panel (SIP) instead.","pos":[8449,8562]},{"content":"To use your computer’s keyboard in the emulator, press F4.","pos":[8565,8623]},{"content":"To stop using your computer’s keyboard in the emulator, press F4.","pos":[8625,8690]},{"content":"The following table lists the keys on a hardware keyboard that you can use to emulate the buttons and other controls on a Windows Phone.","pos":[8692,8828]},{"content":"Note that in Emulator Build 10.0.14332 the computer hardware key mapping was changed.","pos":[8830,8915]},{"content":"Values in the second column of the table below represent these new keys.","pos":[8916,8988]},{"content":"Computer hardware keys (Emulator Build 10.0.14295 and earlier)","pos":[8991,9053]},{"content":"Computer hardware keys (Emulator Build 10.0.14332 and newer)","pos":[9056,9116]},{"content":"Windows Phone hardware button","pos":[9119,9148]},{"content":"Notes","pos":[9151,9156]},{"content":"F1","pos":[9247,9249]},{"content":"WIN + ESC","pos":[9252,9261]},{"content":"BACK","pos":[9264,9268]},{"content":"Long presses work as expected.","pos":[9271,9301]},{"content":"F2","pos":[9302,9304]},{"content":"WIN + F2","pos":[9307,9315]},{"content":"START","pos":[9318,9323]},{"content":"Long presses work as expected.","pos":[9326,9356]},{"content":"F3","pos":[9357,9359]},{"content":"WIN + F3","pos":[9362,9370]},{"content":"SEARCH","pos":[9373,9379]},{"content":"F4","pos":[9384,9386]},{"content":"F4 (no change)","pos":[9389,9403]},{"content":"Toggles between using the local computer’s keyboard and not using the local computer’s keyboard.","pos":[9406,9502]},{"content":"F6","pos":[9506,9508]},{"content":"WIN + F6","pos":[9511,9519]},{"content":"CAMERA HALF","pos":[9522,9533]},{"content":"A dedicated camera button that is pressed halfway.","pos":[9536,9586]},{"content":"F7","pos":[9587,9589]},{"content":"WIN + F7","pos":[9592,9600]},{"content":"CAMERA FULL","pos":[9603,9614]},{"content":"A dedicated camera button.","pos":[9617,9643]},{"content":"F9","pos":[9644,9646]},{"content":"WIN + F9","pos":[9649,9657]},{"content":"VOLUME UP","pos":[9660,9669]},{"content":"F10","pos":[9673,9676]},{"content":"WIN + F10","pos":[9679,9688]},{"content":"VOLUME DOWN","pos":[9691,9702]},{"content":"F12","pos":[9706,9709]},{"content":"WIN + F12","pos":[9712,9721]},{"content":"POWER","pos":[9724,9729]},{"content":"Press the F12 key twice to enable the lock screen.","pos":[9732,9782]},{"content":"Long presses work as expected.","pos":[9783,9813]},{"content":"ESC","pos":[9814,9817]},{"content":"WIN + ESC","pos":[9820,9829]},{"content":"BACK","pos":[9832,9836]},{"content":"Long presses work as expected.","pos":[9839,9869]},{"content":"Near Field Communications (NFC)","pos":[9877,9908]},{"content":"Build and test apps that use Near Field Communication (NFC) enabled features on Windows 10 Mobile by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>NFC<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab of the emulator’s <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Additional Tools<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> menu.","pos":[9910,10077]},{"content":"NFC is useful for a number of scenarios ranging from Proximity scenarios (such as tap to share) to card emulation (such as tap to pay).","pos":[10078,10213]},{"content":"You can test your app by simulating a pair of phones tapping together by using a pair of emulators, or you can test your app by simulating a tap to a tag.","pos":[10215,10369]},{"content":"Also in Windows 10, mobile devices are enabled with HCE (Host Card Emulation) feature and by using the phone emulator you can simulate tapping your device to a payment terminal for APDU command-response traffic.","pos":[10370,10581]},{"content":"The NFC tab supports three modes:","pos":[10583,10616]},{"content":"Proximity Mode","pos":[10622,10636]},{"content":"HCE (Host Card Emulation) Mode","pos":[10641,10671]},{"content":"Smart Card Reader Mode","pos":[10676,10698]},{"content":"In all modes, the emulator window has three areas of interest.","pos":[10700,10762]},{"content":"The top left section is specific to the mode selected.","pos":[10768,10822]},{"content":"The features of this section depend on the mode, and are detailed in the mode-specific sections below.","pos":[10823,10925]},{"content":"The top right section lists the logs.","pos":[10930,10967]},{"content":"When you tap a pair of devices together (or tap to the POS terminal) the tap event is logged and when the devices are untapped the untap event is logged.","pos":[10968,11121]},{"content":"This section also records if your app responded before the connection is broken or any other action you have taken in the emulator UI with time stamps.","pos":[11122,11273]},{"content":"Logs are persistent between mode switches, and you can clear the logs at any point by hitting the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Clear<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button above the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Logs<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> screen.","pos":[11274,11415]},{"content":"The bottom half of the screen is the message log and shows the transcript of all messages sent or received over the currently selected connection, depending on the mode selected.","pos":[11420,11598]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Important<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  When you first launch the tapper tool, you will get a Windows Firewall prompt.","pos":[11602,11695]},{"content":"You MUST select ALL 3 check boxes and allow the tool through the firewall, or the tool will silently fail to work.","pos":[11696,11810]},{"content":"After launching the quick start installer, make sure you follow the above instruction to select all 3 check boxes on the firewall prompt.","pos":[11812,11949]},{"content":"Also, the tapper tool must be installed and used on the same physical host machine as the Microsoft Emulator.","pos":[11950,12059]},{"content":"Proximity mode","pos":[12065,12079]},{"content":"To simulate a pair of phones tapping together you'll need to launch a pair of Windows Phone 8 emulators.","pos":[12081,12185]},{"content":"Since Visual Studio doesn't support running two identical emulators at the same time, you'll need to select different resolutions for each of the emulators to work around it.","pos":[12186,12360]},{"content":"The NFC Proximity page","pos":[12364,12386]},{"pos":[12424,12732],"content":"When you check the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable discovery of peer devices<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> checkbox, the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Peer device<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> dropdown box shows Microsoft Emulators (running on the same physical host machine or in the local network) as well as the Windows machines running the simulator driver (running on the same machine or in the local network)."},{"content":"Once both emulators are running:","pos":[12734,12766]},{"pos":[12772,12845],"content":"Select the emulator you would like to target in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Peer device<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> list."},{"pos":[12850,12898],"content":"Select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Send to peer device<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> radio button."},{"content":"Click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Tap<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button.","pos":[12903,12924]},{"content":"This will simulate the two devices tapping together and you should be hearing the NFC tap notification sound","pos":[12925,13033]},{"pos":[13038,13099],"content":"To disconnect the 2 devices, simply hit the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Untap<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button."},{"content":"Alternatively, you can enable <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Automatically untap in (seconds)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> check box where you can specify the number of seconds you want the devices to be tapped and they will be automatically untapped after the specified number of seconds (simulating what would be expected of a user in real life, they would only hold their phones together for a short time).","pos":[13101,13454]},{"content":"Note however that currently the message log isn't available after the connection has been untapped.","pos":[13455,13554]},{"content":"To simulate reading messages from a tag or receiving messages from another device:","pos":[13556,13638]},{"pos":[13644,13744],"content":"Select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Send to self<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> radio button to test scenarios that require only one NFC enabled device."},{"content":"Click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Tap<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button.","pos":[13749,13770]},{"content":"This will simulate the tapping a device to a tag and you should be hearing the NFC tap notification sound","pos":[13771,13876]},{"pos":[13881,13928],"content":"To disconnect, simply hit the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Untap<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button."},{"content":"Using the proximity mode you can inject messages as if they came from a tag or another peer device.","pos":[13930,14029]},{"content":"The toolallows you to send messages of the following types.","pos":[14030,14089]},{"content":"WindowsURI","pos":[14095,14105]},{"content":"WindowsMime","pos":[14110,14121]},{"content":"WritableTag","pos":[14126,14137]},{"content":"Pairing:Bluetooth","pos":[14142,14159]},{"content":"NDEF","pos":[14164,14168]},{"content":"NDEF:MIME","pos":[14173,14182]},{"content":"NDEF:URI","pos":[14187,14195]},{"content":"NDEF:wkt.U","pos":[14200,14210]},{"content":"You can either create these messages by editing the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Payload<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> windows or providing them in a file.","pos":[14212,14312]},{"content":"For more information about these types and how to use them please refer to the Remarks section of the<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ProximityDevice.PublishBinaryMessage<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh701129)</ept> reference page.","pos":[14313,14530]},{"content":"The Windows 8 Driver Kit (WDK) includes a driver sample that exposes the same protocol as the Windows Phone 8 emulator.","pos":[14532,14651]},{"content":"You'll need to download the DDK, build that sample driver, install it on a Windows 8 device, then add the Windows 8 device's IP address or hostname to the devices list and tap it either with another Windows 8 device or with a Windows Phone 8 emulator.","pos":[14652,14903]},{"content":"Host Card Emulation (HCE) Mode","pos":[14909,14939]},{"content":"In Host Card Emulation (HCE) mode you can test your HCE-based card emulation application by writing your own custom scripts to simulate a smart card reader terminal, such as a Point of Sale (POS) terminal.","pos":[14941,15146]},{"content":"This tool assumes that you are familiar with the command response pairs (compliant with ISO-7816-4) that are sent between a reader terminal (such as POS, badge reader or transit card reader) and the smart card (that you are emulating in your application).","pos":[15147,15402]},{"content":"The NFC HCE page","pos":[15406,15422]},{"content":"Create a new script by clicking the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Add<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button in the script editor section.","pos":[15458,15538]},{"content":"You can provide a name for your script and after you are done with editing, you can save your script using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Save<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button.","pos":[15539,15666]},{"content":"Your saved scripts will be available the next time you launch the emulator.","pos":[15671,15746]},{"content":"Run your scripts by hitting the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Play<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button in the scripts editor window.","pos":[15751,15828]},{"content":"This action results in simulating of tapping your phone to the terminal and sending commands written in your script.","pos":[15829,15945]},{"content":"Alternatively you can hit the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Tap<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button and then the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Play<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> button, until you hit <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Play<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> the script will not run.","pos":[15946,16068]},{"pos":[16073,16245],"content":"Stop sending commands by hitting the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Stop<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button, which stops sending the commands to your application but the devices remain tapped until you hit the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Untap<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> button."},{"pos":[16250,16345],"content":"Delete your scripts by selecting the script in the dropdown menu and hitting <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Delete<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button."},{"content":"The emulator tool does not check for the syntax of your scripts until you run the script using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Play<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button.","pos":[16350,16465]},{"content":"The messages sent by your script are dependent on your implementation of your card emulation app.","pos":[16466,16563]},{"pos":[16565,16727],"content":"You can also use the terminal simulator tool from MasterCard (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>https://www.terminalsimulator.com/<ept id=\"p1\">](https://www.terminalsimulator.com/ )</ept>) for payments app testing."},{"pos":[16733,16856],"content":"Check the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable MasterCard<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> listener checkbox below the script editor windows and launch the simulator from MasterCard."},{"content":"Using the tool, you can generate commands that are relayed to your application running on the emulator through the NFC tool.","pos":[16861,16985]},{"pos":[16987,17162],"content":"To learn more about HCE support and how to develop HCE apps in Windows 10 Mobile, please refer to the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft NFC Team Blog<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=534749)</ept>."},{"content":"How to Create Scripts for HCE Testing","pos":[17168,17205]},{"pos":[17207,17505],"content":"The scripts are written as C# code and your script’s Run method is called when you click the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Play<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button, this method takes an IScriptProcessor interface which is used to transceive APDU commands, output to the log window, and control the timeout for waiting on an APDU response from the phone."},{"content":"Below is a reference on what functionality is available:","pos":[17507,17563]},{"content":"Smart Card Reader Mode","pos":[18268,18290]},{"content":"The emulator can be connected to a smart card reader device on your host computer, such that smart cards inserted or tapped will show up to your phone application and can be communicated to with APDUs using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Windows.Devices.SmartCards.SmartCardConnection<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Dn608002)</ept> class.","pos":[18292,18620]},{"content":"For this to work, you will need a compatible smart card reader device attached to your computer, USB smart card readers (both NFC/contactless and insert/contact) are widely available.","pos":[18621,18804]},{"content":"To enable the emulator to work with an attached smart card reader, first choose the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Card Reader<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> mode which should show a dropdown box listing all the compatible smart card readers attached to the host system, then choose the smart card reader device you’d like to be connected from the dropdown.","pos":[18805,19104]},{"content":"Note that not all NFC-capable smart card readers support some types of NFC cards, and some do not support the standard PC/SC storage card APDU commands.","pos":[19106,19258]},{"content":"Multi-point input","pos":[19263,19280]},{"content":"Simulate multi-touch input for pinching and zooming, rotating, and panning objects by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Multi-touch Input<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button on the emulator toolbar.","pos":[19282,19431]},{"content":"This feature is useful if your app displays photos, maps, or other visual elements that users can pinch and zoom, rotate, or pan.","pos":[19432,19561]},{"content":"Tap the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Multi-touch Input<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button on the emulator toolbar to enable multi-point input.","pos":[19567,19656]},{"content":"Two touch points appear on the emulator screen around a center point.","pos":[19657,19726]},{"content":"Right-click and drag one of the touch points to position them without touching the screen.","pos":[19731,19821]},{"content":"Left-click and drag one of the touch points to simulate pinching and zooming, rotating, or panning.","pos":[19826,19925]},{"pos":[19930,20016],"content":"Tap the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Single Point Input<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button on the emulator toolbar to restore normal input."},{"content":"The following screenshot shows multi-touch input.","pos":[20018,20067]},{"pos":[20073,20157],"content":"The small left image shows the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Multi-touch Input<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button on the emulator toolbar."},{"pos":[20162,20280],"content":"The middle image shows the emulator screen after tapping the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Multi-touch Input<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button to display the touch points."},{"content":"The right image shows the emulator screen after dragging the touch points to zoom the image.","pos":[20285,20377]},{"content":"Multi-point input option on the Emulator toolbar","pos":[20381,20429]},{"content":"Accelerometer","pos":[20461,20474]},{"pos":[20476,20597],"content":"Test apps that track the movement of the phone by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Accelerometer<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab of the emulator's <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Additional Tools<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"content":"You can test the accelerometer sensor with live input or pre-recorded input.","pos":[20599,20675]},{"content":"The only type of recorded data that’s available simulates shaking the phone.","pos":[20676,20752]},{"content":"You can’t record or save your own simulations for the accelerometer.","pos":[20753,20821]},{"pos":[20827,20905],"content":"Select the desired starting orientation in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Orientation<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> drop-down list."},{"content":"Select the type of input.","pos":[20915,20940]},{"content":"To run the simulation with live input","pos":[20952,20989]},{"content":"In the middle of the accelerometer simulator, drag the colored dot to simulate movement of the device in a 3D plane.","pos":[21001,21117]},{"content":"Moving the dot on the horizontal access rotates the simulator from side to side.","pos":[21127,21207]},{"content":"Moving the dot on the vertical access rotates the simulator back and forth, rotating around the x-axis.","pos":[21208,21311]},{"content":"As you drag the dot, the X, Y, and Z coordinates update based on the rotation calculations.","pos":[21312,21403]},{"content":"You cannot move the dot outside the bounding circle in the touch pad area.","pos":[21404,21478]},{"pos":[21488,21552],"content":"Optionally, click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Reset<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to restore the starting orientation."},{"content":"To run the simulation with recorded input","pos":[21564,21605]},{"content":"In the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Recorded Data<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> section, click the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Play<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> button to start playback of the simulated data.","pos":[21617,21717]},{"content":"The only option available in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Recorded Data<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> list is shake.","pos":[21718,21783]},{"content":"The simulator does not move on the screen when it plays back the data.","pos":[21784,21854]},{"content":"Accelerometer page in Additional Tools for the Emulator","pos":[21858,21913]},{"content":"Location and driving","pos":[21948,21968]},{"content":"Test apps that use navigation or geofencing by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Location<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab of the emulator's <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Additional Tools<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[21970,22083]},{"content":"This feature is useful for simulating driving, biking, or walking in conditions similar to the real world.","pos":[22084,22190]},{"content":"You can test your app while you simulate moving from one location to another at different speeds and with different accuracy profiles.","pos":[22192,22326]},{"content":"The location simulator can help you to identify changes in your usage of the location APIs usage that improve the user experience.","pos":[22327,22457]},{"content":"For example, the tool can help you identify that you have to tune geofence parameters, such as size or dwell time, to detect the geofences successfully in different scenarios.","pos":[22458,22633]},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Location<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab supports three modes.","pos":[22635,22677]},{"content":"In all modes, when the emulator receives a new position, that position is available to trigger the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PositionChanged<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR225540)</ept> event or to respond to a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>GetGeopositionAsync<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh973536)</ept> call in your location-aware app.","pos":[22678,22998]},{"content":"In <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Pin<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> mode, you place pushpins on the map.","pos":[23004,23051]},{"content":"When you click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Play all points<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, the location simulator sends the location of each pin to the emulator one after another, at the interval specified in the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Seconds per pin<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> text box.","pos":[23052,23239]},{"content":"In <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Live<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> mode, you place pushpins on the map.","pos":[23245,23293]},{"content":"The location simulator sends the location of each pin to the emulator immediately as you place them on the map.","pos":[23294,23405]},{"content":"In <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Route<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> mode, you place pushpins on the map to indicate waypoints, and the location simulator automatically calculates a route.","pos":[23411,23543]},{"content":"The route includes invisible pins at one-second intervals along the route.","pos":[23544,23618]},{"content":"For example, if you have select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Walking<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> speed profile, which assumes a speed of 5 kilometers per hour, then invisible pins are generated at intervals of 1.39 meters.","pos":[23619,23792]},{"content":"When you click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Play all points<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, the location simulator sends the location of each pin to the emulator one after another, at the interval determined by the speed profile selected in the drop-down list.","pos":[23793,23997]},{"content":"In all modes of the location simulator, you can do the following things.","pos":[23999,24071]},{"pos":[24077,24135],"content":"You can search for a location by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Search<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> box."},{"pos":[24141,24189],"content":"You can <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Zoom in<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Zoom out<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> on the map."},{"content":"You can save the current set of data points to an XML file, and reload the file later to reuse the same data points.","pos":[24195,24311]},{"pos":[24317,24384],"content":"You can <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Toggle pushpin mode on or off<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Clear all points<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"content":"In Pin and Route mode, you can also do the following things.","pos":[24386,24446]},{"content":"Save a route you created for later use.","pos":[24452,24491]},{"content":"Load a route previously created.","pos":[24497,24529]},{"content":"You can even load route files created in previous versions of the tool.","pos":[24530,24601]},{"content":"Modify a route by deleting pushpins (in Pin mode) or waypoints (in Route mode).","pos":[24607,24686]},{"content":"Accuracy profiles","pos":[24690,24707]},{"pos":[24711,24848],"content":"In all modes of the location simulator, you can select one of the following accuracy profiles in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Accuracy profile<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> drop-down list."},{"content":"Profile","pos":[24852,24859]},{"content":"Description","pos":[24863,24874]},{"content":"Pinpoint","pos":[24984,24992]},{"content":"Assumes perfectly accurate location readings.","pos":[24995,25040]},{"content":"This setting is not realistic, but it's useful for testing the logic of your app.","pos":[25041,25122]},{"content":"Urban","pos":[25128,25133]},{"content":"Assumes that buildings are restricting the number of satellites in view, but there is often a high density of cell towers and Wi-Fi access points that can be used for positioning.","pos":[25139,25318]},{"content":"Suburban","pos":[25323,25331]},{"content":"Assumes that satellite positioning is relatively good and there is good density of cell towers, but the density of Wi-Fi access points is not high.","pos":[25334,25481]},{"content":"Rural","pos":[25487,25492]},{"content":"Assumes that satellite positioning is good, but there is low density of cell towers and almost no Wi-Fi access points that can be used for positioning.","pos":[25498,25649]},{"content":"Speed profiles","pos":[25655,25669]},{"pos":[25673,25765],"content":"In <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Route<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> mode, you can select one of the following speed profiles in the drop-down list."},{"content":"Profile","pos":[25769,25776]},{"content":"Speed per hour","pos":[25779,25793]},{"content":"Speed per second","pos":[25810,25826]},{"content":"Description","pos":[25829,25840]},{"content":"Speed Limit","pos":[25922,25933]},{"content":"Speed limit of the route","pos":[25936,25960]},{"content":"Not applicable","pos":[25963,25977]},{"content":"Traverse the route at the posted speed limit.","pos":[25982,26027]},{"content":"Walking","pos":[26032,26039]},{"content":"5 km/h","pos":[26046,26052]},{"content":"1.39 m","pos":[26073,26079]},{"content":"Traverse the route at a natural walking pace of 5 km/h.","pos":[26092,26147]},{"content":"Biking","pos":[26152,26158]},{"content":"25 km/h","pos":[26166,26173]},{"content":"6.94 m","pos":[26193,26199]},{"content":"Traverse the route at a natural biking pace of 25 km/h.","pos":[26212,26267]},{"content":"Fast","pos":[26272,26276]},{"content":"Traverse the route faster than the posted speed limit.","pos":[26331,26385]},{"content":"Route mode","pos":[26392,26402]},{"content":"Route mode has the following features and limitations.","pos":[26406,26460]},{"content":"Route mode requires an Internet connection.","pos":[26466,26509]},{"content":"When the Urban, Suburban, or Rural accuracy profile is selected, the location simulator calculates a simulated satellite-based position, a simulated Wi-Fi position, and a simulated cellular position for each pin.","pos":[26515,26727]},{"content":"Your app receives only one of these positions.","pos":[26728,26774]},{"content":"The three sets of coordinates for the current location are displayed in different colors on the map and in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Current location<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> list.","pos":[26775,26912]},{"content":"The accuracy of the pins along route the route is not uniform.","pos":[26918,26980]},{"content":"Some of the pins use satellite accuracy, some use Wi-Fi accuracy, and some use cellular accuracy.","pos":[26981,27078]},{"content":"You cannot select more than 20 waypoints for the route.","pos":[27084,27139]},{"content":"Positions for the visible and invisible pins on the map are generated only once when you select a new accuracy profile.","pos":[27145,27264]},{"content":"When you play the route more than once with the same accuracy profile during the same emulator session, the previously generated positions are reused.","pos":[27265,27415]},{"content":"The following screenshot shows Route mode.","pos":[27417,27459]},{"content":"The orange line indicates the route.","pos":[27460,27496]},{"content":"The blue dot indicates the accurate location of the car determined by satellite-based positioning.","pos":[27497,27595]},{"content":"The red and green dots indicate less accurate locations calculated by using Wi-Fi and cellular positioning and the Suburban accuracy profile.","pos":[27596,27737]},{"content":"The three calculated locations are also displayed in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Current location<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> list.","pos":[27738,27821]},{"content":"Location page in Additional Tools for the Emulator","pos":[27825,27875]},{"content":"More info about the location simulator","pos":[27901,27939]},{"content":"You can request a position with the accuracy set to Default.","pos":[27947,28007]},{"content":"A limitation that existed in the Windows Phone 8 version of the location simulator, and required you to request a position with the accuracy set to High, has been fixed.","pos":[28008,28177]},{"content":"When you test geofencing in the emulator, create a simulation that gives the geofencing engine a “warm-up” period to learn and adjust to the movement patterns.","pos":[28183,28342]},{"content":"The only position properties that are simulated are the Latitude, Longitude, Accuracy, and PositionSource.","pos":[28348,28454]},{"content":"The location simulator does not simulate other properties such as Speed, Heading, and so forth.","pos":[28455,28550]},{"content":"Network","pos":[28555,28562]},{"content":"Test your app with different network speeds and different signal strengths by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Network<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab of the emulator's <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Additional Tools<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[28564,28707]},{"content":"This feature is useful if your app calls web services or transfers data.","pos":[28708,28780]},{"content":"The network simulation feature helps you to make sure that your app runs well in the real world.","pos":[28782,28878]},{"content":"The Windows Phone Emulator runs on a computer that usually has a fast WiFi or Ethernet connection.","pos":[28879,28977]},{"content":"Your app, however, runs on phones that are typically connected over a slower cellular connection.","pos":[28978,29075]},{"pos":[29081,29195],"content":"Check <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable network simulation<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to test your app with different network speeds and different signal strengths."},{"pos":[29200,29276],"content":"In the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Network speed<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> dropdown list, select one of the following options:"},{"content":"No network","pos":[29285,29295]},{"content":"2G","pos":[29304,29306]},{"content":"3G","pos":[29315,29317]},{"content":"4G","pos":[29326,29328]},{"pos":[29334,29412],"content":"In the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Signal strength<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> dropdown list, select one of the following options:"},{"content":"Good","pos":[29421,29425]},{"content":"Average","pos":[29434,29441]},{"content":"Poor","pos":[29450,29454]},{"pos":[29460,29590],"content":"Clear <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable network simulation<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to restore the default behavior, which uses the network settings of your development computer."},{"pos":[29592,29664],"content":"You can also review the current network settings on the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Network<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab."},{"content":"Network page in Additional Tools for the Emulator","pos":[29668,2